<div class="tab-content">
  <div class="tab-pane fade show active" id="users-tab-pane" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="users-tab" tabindex="0">
    <div class="alert alert-info">
      <details>
        <summary><strong>Document too long? Have a TL;DR!</strong></summary>
        <p class="pt-2">
          Certificates are XIVAuth's notary service. You can use it to prove that something actually came from you, or to
          make sure that only you can read some information sent to you. Since certificates can be verified offline, they
          can unlock powerful use cases for building trust.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-0">
          However, it's important to understand that certificates are not a silver bullet. They're primarily intended for
          high-assurance or decentralized systems and require careful implementation and user awareness. Certificates are
          <strong>not</strong> a prerequisite for a system to be secure or trustworthy, and there are very good reasons to
          not use them.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>

    <h2>What is a certificate?</h2>

    <p>
      Fundamentally, a certificate is a digital proof of an identity. Certificates have two major uses: <em>signing</em>
      data (proving it came from you) and <em>encrypting</em> data (scrambling it so only the intended recipient can
      read it). In the former case, a certificate is the functional equivalent of a wax seal on an official document
      certifying it came from a specific entity. In the latter, the certificate is the equivalent of a lockbox and key;
      anyone may place anything into a lockbox, but only the owner can open it.
    </p>

    <p>
      When you create a certificate, your computer generates two mathematically linked keys: a private key and a public
      key. The private key is kept secret and is known only to you (or your computer), while the public key can be
      shared freely with anyone. Only the holder of the private key may sign (or "apply the seal") or decrypt ("open the
      lockbox") data through the certificate.
    </p>

    <p>
      XIVAuth acts as the authority that ties your public key to a verified character. When XIVAuth issues a
      certificate, it is essentially saying <em>"we're vouching that this seal and lockbox belong to this
      character."</em> So long as you trust XIVAuth to assert identities, and so long as you trust that your private key
      has not been stolen, you have implicit trust in that certificate.
    </p>

    <p>
      Certificates, however, have another special property: they can be verified fully offline and independently. This
      means that any data signed by a certificate can be independently verified by anyone without involving XIVAuth at
      all. This allows for trust relationships to be created quickly and efficiently, allowing users to bootstrap trust
      with minimal technical overhead.
    </p>

    <h2 class="pt-3">Why would I use a certificate?</h2>

    <p>
      Certificates have a few uses in the XIVAuth ecosystem. Developers may use them in creative and unique ways, but
      common use cases include:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li class="my-3">
        <strong>Proving data came from your character.</strong><br>
        By signing some data with your certificate, other parties can (reasonably) trust that it came from you and not
        from a third party. This is particularly useful for proving ownership (or authenticity) of data: a digitally
        signed message in your name means that you are the one who wrote it.
      </li>
      <li class="my-3">
        <strong>Encrypting data for others.</strong><br>
        If you have a copy of a certificate for another player, you can encrypt data that only they can read. This
        allows the creation of secure channels for information without permitting eavesdropping by third parties. As an
        example, you can send a private message to another character and keep it truly private.
      </li>
      <li class="my-3">
        <strong>Authenticating to a service.</strong><br>
        Some services may choose to use a certificate for authentication purposes instead of a username and password.
        Since certificates tend to have reasonably long lives and private keys cannot be guessed, anyone holding a
        certificate can prove who they are.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      In most computer systems, certificates are also stored in a secure container. This means that your operating
      system has built-in protections to secure your private keys, making it harder to steal or tamper with them. Most
      critically, XIVAuth uses a system called a Certificate Signing Request, which means that private keys are never
      given to XIVAuth. Keys are generated locally, and your public key (and some metadata) is sent to XIVAuth's systems
      through our API.
    </p>

    <h2 class="pt-3">What's the downside?</h2>
    <div class="alert alert-warning d-flex">
      <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle-fill me-2"></i>
      <span>
        XIVAuth specifically recommends against using certificates unless necessary. They are powerful but complex, and
        require careful implementation and user awareness to use safely. Using certificates does not make a service
        "more secure" just as <em>not</em> using certificates wouldn't make it "less secure". It comes down
        entirely to a service's design, intent, threat model, and needs.
      </span>
    </div>

    <p>
      Certificates are not the right tool for every situation. Most services already have a central point of trust: the
      service itself. If users are willing to trust the service to be fair and honest, certificates add complexity
      without meaningful benefit. Their value is in high-assurance settings or systems where no single party can vouch
      for identities, or where offline verification is essential. In essence, certificates allow services that cannot
      offer their own trust guarantees to "borrow" that trust from a service like XIVAuth.
    </p>

    <p>
      When certificates are appropriate, they still carry fundamental requirements. At a minimum, two separate
      conditions must remain true: the certificate authority (in this case, XIVAuth) must be trustworthy to all parties,
      and the certificate holder must retain sole control over their private key. If either condition is no longer true,
      a certificate can no longer be trusted.
    </p>

    <p>
      Beyond that, users need to be cautious about which applications they allow to request certificates. A malicious or
      poorly-built application may not generate or store private keys properly. For example, if a private key is
      escrowed improperly in a service's database, that keypair can no longer be trusted. Certificate revocation exists
      to address this, but it requires user intervention and cannot be automated. Certificates are also
      <em>extremely</em> complex; implementation mistakes are easy to make, are often subtle, and can carry serious
      consequences.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="tab-pane fade" id="developers-tab-pane" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="developers-tab" tabindex="0">
    <h2>Implementation Guidance</h2>

    <p>
      Before you decide to use certificates in your project, I would highly recommend
      <a href="https://rip-van-webble.blogspot.com/2021/03/certificates-confuse-everything.html">this wonderful blog
        post</a> from someone with far more intelligence and experience than me explaining a lot of the less-obvious
      aspects to certificates. Despite building out a full certificate authority myself, I still
      <strong>strongly</strong> recommend that developers avoid implementing certificate-based systems unless necessary.
      Generally, this comes down to most or all of these factors being present:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>You need a system that provides bindings of public keys to (public) identities.</li>
      <li>You're building a system that is unable or unwilling to vouch for identities.</li>
      <li>Your system needs the ability to verify identities <em>offline</em> without any server interactions.</li>
      <li>You need a system capable of providing or consuming publicly auditable artifacts.</li>
      <li>
        There is no better alternative for public key distribution such as DNS or a GPG-like registry. (Or, a publicly
        queryable registry is undesirable).
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Implementing and supporting PKI/X.509 is a very complex task, and many things can very easily go wrong. Even my
      implementation (made by someone who generally knows what they're doing!) contains a couple known tradeoffs (read:
      flaws) that I considered acceptable for a project providing SSO for a video game. These aren't security-critical
      by any means, but they show the sheer complexity of running a certificate authority. Certificates and a full X.509
      implementation aren't <em>quite</em> a last resort, but they're certainly pretty close. Make sure you know what
      you're signing up for.
    </p>

    <p>
      If, despite all of this, you still feel that a certificate-based system is the right choice for your needs, please
      consider reaching out to me in the <%= link_to "XIVAuth Discord", discord_path %>. I'd be happy to chat about your
      use case and offer any advice or guidance I can to make sure you don't shoot yourself in the foot.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>